S-T-S, and cross-account access.

S-T-S, the Security Token Service, is the engine that mints temporary credentials whenever a role is assumed. It returns an access key I-D, a secret access key, a session token, and an expiration somewhere between fifteen minutes and twelve hours. After that, the credentials simply stop working, and that's exactly why roles are safer than long-lived keys.

There are five flavors of the assume-role call. Plain assume-role, for same-account or cross-account. Assume-role-with-SAML, for enterprise identity providers like A-D-F-S, Okta, and Ping. Assume-role-with-web-identity, for O-I-D-C providers like Cognito, Google, E-K-S, and GitHub Actions. Get-session-token, to wrap an existing user's keys with M-F-A. And get-federation-token, for a custom broker you build yourself. On E-C-2, an instance profile wraps a role and the metadata service vends rotating credentials automatically. Lambda execution roles and E-C-S task roles do the same. So you never plant a long-lived key on a box.

Cross-account access has two shapes. With role assumption, the resource account creates a role that trusts the caller's account; the caller calls assume-role and becomes the role, so their original identity is dropped. With a resource-based policy, the resource account names the caller's principal directly in the resource's own policy, and the caller keeps their identity end to end. One guard rail matters when a third-party vendor assumes a role in your account: the confused-deputy problem. You require an external-I-D, a secret that only you and the vendor share, so that another of the vendor's customers can't trick them into reaching into your account. And when it's an AWS service calling on your behalf, you use source-A-R-N or source-account instead.
